ther, and James’s could spend an evening with dead companions.By following the path by which ostensibly unremarkable entities come to voice, Quiet Testimony suggests new configurations for ethics, politics, and the literary.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aWitness bearing (Christianity) in literature. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aDouglass.  aEmerson.  aHenry James.  aMelville.  aethics.  aliterary.  aquiet.  asilence.  atestimony.  awitnessing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823254798zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823254798423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823254798/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK